label.value: negative regulation of multicellular organism growth

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of growth of an organism to reach its usual body size.
The first few specialized divisions of an activated animal egg.
Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of locomotion of a cell or organism.

label.value: positive regulation of multicellular organism growth

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of growth of an organism to reach its usual body size.
Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of embryonic development.

Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of meiotic nuclear division, the process in which the nucleus of a diploid cell divides twice forming four haploid cells, one or more of which usually function as gametes.
The determination of sex and sexual phenotype in the germ line of a hermaphrodite.
The determination of female sex and sexual phenotype in the germ-line of the hermaphrodite.

The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the dauer larva over time, through the facultative diapause of the dauer (enduring) larval stage, with specialized traits adapted for dispersal and long-term survival, with elevated stress resistance and without feeding.

The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the egg-laying organ of female and hermaphrodite nematodes over time, from its formation to the mature structure. In nematodes, the vulva is formed from ventral epidermal cells during larval stages to give rise to a fully formed vulva in the adult.

Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of development of the vulva. Vulval development is the process whose specific outcome is the progression of the egg-laying organ of female and hermaphrodite nematodes over time, from its formation to the mature structure. In nematodes, the vulva is formed from ventral epidermal cells during larval stages to give rise to a fully formed vulva in the adult.

Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of development of the vulva. Vulval development is the process whose specific outcome is the progression of the egg-laying organ of female and hermaphrodite nematodes over time, from its formation to the mature structure. In nematodes, the vulva is formed from ventral epidermal cells during larval stages to give rise to a fully formed vulva in the adult.

Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of development of the vulva. Vulval development is the process whose specific outcome is the progression of the egg-laying organ of female and hermaphrodite nematodes over time, from its formation to the mature structure. In nematodes, the vulva is formed from ventral epidermal cells during larval stages to give rise to a fully formed vulva in the adult.

A process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of gene expression through chromatin remodeling either by modifying higher order chromatin fiber structure, nucleosomal histones, or cytosine methylation of DNA. Once established, this regulation may be maintained over many cell divisions. It can also be heritable in the absence of the instigating signal.
The covalent alteration of one or more nucleotides within snRNA, resulting in a change in the properties of the snRNA.
The process in which the anatomical structures of the post-embryonic soma are generated and organized.

definition.value: Note that this term was 'body morphogenesis (sensu Nematoda)'.

value.value: A post-transcriptional gene silencing pathway mediated by the action of small regulatory non-coding RNAs (sRNAs). sRNAs are 20-500 nucleotides in length and found in bacteria.

definition.value: It is postulated that there 3 mechanisms of sRNA-mediated gene silencing: (i) translation inhibition, (ii) RNA destabilization, and (iii) transcription termination loop formation (as this is common when looking at riboswitches). sRNA mediated gene silencing is sometimes referred to as 'regulation of riboswitch'.

value.value: Any process that modulates the consistent predetermined time point at which an integrated living unit or organism progresses from an initial condition to a later condition and the rate at which this time point is reached.

label.value: regulation of fibroblast growth factor receptor signaling pathway

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of fibroblast growth factor receptor signaling pathway activity.

label.value: negative regulation of fibroblast growth factor receptor signaling pathway

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of fibroblast growth factor receptor signaling pathway activity.

label.value: polar body extrusion after meiotic divisions

value.value: The cell cycle process in which two small cells are generated, as byproducts destined to degenerate, as a result of the first and second meiotic divisions of a primary oocyte during its development to a mature ovum. One polar body is formed in the first division of meiosis and the other in the second division; at each division, the cytoplasm divides unequally, so that the polar body is of much smaller size than the developing oocyte. At the second division in which a polar body is formed, the polar body and the developing oocyte each contain a haploid set of chromosomes.

Migration of a cell in a multicellular organism that, having changed its location, is required to induce normal properties in one or more cells at its new location. An example of this would be the distal tip cells of Caenorhabditis elegans.
Behavior that is dependent upon the sensation of temperature.

label.value: translocation of peptides or proteins into host

value.value: The directed movement of peptides or proteins produced by an organism to a location inside its host organism. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.
The determination of sex and sexual phenotypes in a hermaphroditic organism's soma. An example of this is found in Caenorhabditis elegans.
Promotion of male sex and sexual phenotypes in the hermaphroditic nematode soma. An example of this is found in Caenorhabditis elegans.
Promotion of female sex and sexual phenotypes in the hermaphroditic soma. An example of this is found in Caenorhabditis elegans.
The determination of male sex and sexual phenotype in the germ-line of the hermaphrodite. An example of this is found in Caenorhabditis elegans.
Binding to interleukin-18.
Combining with interleukin-18 and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity.
Binding to interleukin-15.
Combining with interleukin-15 and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity.
Binding to interleukin-16.
Combining with interleukin-16 and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity.
Binding to interleukin-19.
Combining with interleukin-19 and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity.
Binding to interleukin-20.
Combining with interleukin-20 and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity.
Binding to interleukin-22.
Combining with interleukin-22 and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity.
Binding to interleukin-23.
Combining with interleukin-23 and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity.

label.value: granulocyte macrophage colony-stimulating factor complex binding

value.value: Binding to a granulocyte macrophage colony-stimulating factor complex.
A protein complex that binds interleukin-12 and that consists of, at a minimum, a dimeric interleukin and its two receptor subunits as well as optional additional kinase subunits.

Regulated re-replication of DNA within a single cell cycle, resulting in an increased cell ploidy. An example of this process occurs in the synthesis of Drosophila salivary gland cell polytene chromosomes.

definition.value: Note that this term is only to be used in situations were this process occurs normally. Not to be used to describe mutant or diseased states.

value.value: A membrane-bounded organelle as it is found in the host cell in which chromosomes are housed and replicated. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.
The process carried out by a cell that restores the biological activity of an unfolded or misfolded protein, using helper proteins such as chaperones.
Binds to and stops, prevents or reduces an ATP hydrolysis activity.
The methylation of peptidyl-L-histidine to form peptidyl-L-1'-methyl-L-histidine (otherwise known as tau-methylhistidine, tele-methylhistidine).
The incorporation of a metal into a metallo-molybdopterin complex.
